Here are the **key differences between Deterministic and Non-Deterministic Algorithms** in a **clear and interview-friendly format**.

---

# Difference Between Deterministic and Non-Deterministic Algorithms

| Feature         | Deterministic Algorithm                                | Non-Deterministic Algorithm                          |
| --------------- | ------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------- |
| Output          | Always produces the **same output for the same input** | May produce **different outputs for the same input** |
| Randomness      | No randomness involved                                 | Uses randomness or probability                       |
| Predictability  | Fully predictable                                      | Not fully predictable                                |
| Execution Path  | Follows a **single fixed path**                        | May explore **multiple possible paths**              |
| Reproducibility | Same result every run                                  | Results may vary between runs                        |

---

# Deterministic Algorithm

A **deterministic algorithm** always produces the **same result when given the same input**.

### Example

* Linear Regression
* Binary Search
* Decision Trees (with fixed parameters)

Example:
If you run **Linear Regression** on the same dataset multiple times, you get **exactly the same model parameters**.

---

# Non-Deterministic Algorithm

A **non-deterministic algorithm** may produce **different results each time it runs**, even with the same input.

This happens because the algorithm involves **random initialization or probabilistic choices**.

### Examples

* Random Forest
* K-Means Clustering
* Genetic Algorithms

Example:
In **K-Means**, cluster centers are **randomly initialized**, so different runs may produce **different clusters**.

---

# Simple Interview Answer

> A deterministic algorithm always produces the same output for the same input, while a non-deterministic algorithm may produce different outputs because it involves randomness or probabilistic decisions.

