Here are the **important points** for the **difference between Oversampling and Undersampling** and **when to use each method**.

---

# Difference Between Oversampling and Undersampling

| Feature   | Oversampling                               | Undersampling                        |
| --------- | ------------------------------------------ | ------------------------------------ |
| Idea      | Increase samples of **minority class**     | Reduce samples of **majority class** |
| Method    | Duplicate or generate new minority samples | Remove some majority samples         |
| Data Size | Dataset size **increases**                 | Dataset size **decreases**           |
| Risk      | May cause **overfitting**                  | May cause **loss of information**    |
| Use Case  | When minority class is very small          | When dataset is very large           |

---

# 1️⃣ Oversampling

Oversampling **balances the dataset by increasing the minority class samples**.

### Methods

* Random Oversampling
* **SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique)**

### Example

Dataset:

| Class     | Samples |
| --------- | ------- |
| Fraud     | 100     |
| Non-Fraud | 1000    |

After oversampling:

| Class     | Samples |
| --------- | ------- |
| Fraud     | 1000    |
| Non-Fraud | 1000    |

---

# 2️⃣ Undersampling

Undersampling **balances the dataset by reducing the majority class samples**.

Example:

| Class     | Samples |
| --------- | ------- |
| Fraud     | 100     |
| Non-Fraud | 1000    |

After undersampling:

| Class     | Samples |
| --------- | ------- |
| Fraud     | 100     |
| Non-Fraud | 100     |

---

# When to Use Which Method

### Use Oversampling when

* Minority class is **very small**
* Losing data is **not acceptable**
* Important cases like **fraud detection or disease detection**

---

### Use Undersampling when

* Dataset is **very large**
* Training time needs to be **reduced**
* Majority class dominates heavily

---

# Advanced Method

**SMOTE**

Creates **synthetic minority samples instead of duplicating existing data**, which helps reduce overfitting.

---

# Simple Interview Answer

> Oversampling increases the number of minority class samples, while undersampling reduces the number of majority class samples to balance the dataset. Oversampling is preferred when the minority class is very small, while undersampling is useful when the dataset is very large.

---

